data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree → regular lambda

The overload now takes `Func<…>` instead of `Expression<Func<…>>`. Your expression-tree building code **won't compile**. Replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — conditionals go directly inside the lambda.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two sub-changes

**a) Uniquification:** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column — now one gets `Street1`. To keep the old (shared) column name, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested full-path naming:** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was column `BillingAddress_City` — now it becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **If you're adding a migration on upgrade**, either pin column names as above to avoid a schema diff, or generate a migration and verify the renames are intentional.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gains a `string logCommandText` parameter (contains SQL with constants redacted). Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Apply the same `string logCommandText` addition to any other methods you implement (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
